properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall expected today. Snow is expected to continue spreading north over Northeastern Ontario this morning. Snow will continue this afternoon and evening before ending overnight. Total snowfall accumulations of 5 to 15 cm are possible with this event with the highest amounts expected near the Quebec border. Although the snowfall amounts are not expected to meet the Snowfall Warning criteria of 15 cm or greater in 12 hours or less, there may be periods of heavy snow today that may make travel difficult. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow continues with snow squalls developing by this morning. Hazards: 5 to 15 cm of snow Heavy snowfall at times Timing: Widespread snow will continue into this morning. Impacts: Hazardous road conditions Discussion: Snow continues across the region. In particular, a band of heavy snow has developed along the eastern Lake Huron shoreline and south across Middlesex County and western Elgin County. This band should gradually weaken and shift northeastwards with time. Snow Squalls should start developing off Lake Huron in the coming hours...and Snow Squall Warnings will likely be needed. Please refer to the Snow Squall Watch in effect for these details. A widespread 5 to 15 cm is expected by morning from widespread snowfall. Reports of 5 to 8 cm of snow have been received so far. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Several hours of freezing rain is possible this morning, particularly over higher terrain. Places along the Ottawa River, such as Pembroke and Petawawa, are not expected to be impacted by freezing rain as much as higher terrain areas to the southwest. Hazards: Several hours of freezing rain, particularly over higher terrain Ice accretion of up to 5 mm Timing: Freezing rain will continue at times this morning before transitioning to scattered flurries with a risk of freezing drizzle this afternoon Impacts: Local power outages may be possible due to ice build-up Generally, impacts should be mainly confined to areas of higher terrain, but places along the Ottawa River may still get into a couple hours of freezing rain by this morning. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots will become icy, slippery and hazardous. Utility outages may occur. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A potent winter storm will impact southern Baffin Island and northern Kivalliq beginning Saturday evening. This storm will bring significant winds, with gusts in excess of 90 km/h possible. This system will also bring 10 to 20 cm of snow to some communities. These winds combined with the falling snow will lead to significantly reduced visibilities in blowing snow, possibly creating blizzard conditions. Conditions will gradually improve Sunday evening for southern Baffin Island and on Monday for northern Kivalliq. Please stay alert to updated bulletins as warnings will likely be issued as the system approaches. Refer to local forecasts for more information on when the inclement weather is expected and specific snowfall amounts. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Winter storm watches are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls are occurring. Hazards: Locally 25 to 45 cm of snow Quickly accumulating snow of 5+ cm per hour Blowing snow Poor visibility in heavy and blowing snow Timing: Now through this morning Impacts: Hazardous to dangerous travel Discussion: Exeter weather RADAR shows a snow squall coming off Lake Huron at Grand Bend within a broader area of moderate snowfall. This snow squall should get more intense over the next several hours. A weather spotter in Parkhill has reported 16 cm of snow so far from system snow and now this band as of 4:30 a.m. Intense snowfall rates may be possible for several hours this morning before the band shifts north this afternoon. Blowing snow may accompany this snow squall as well. Travel could be dangerous. Note: heavy snow from the main low pressure system will continue in these areas as well over the next few hours. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Warm, wet and windy conditions for today and Saturday followed by periods of snow on Saturday evening. Total rainfall: 25 to 50 mm. Locally 60 mm possible. Total snowfall: locally 5 to 10 cm, especially over higher terrain. Maximum wind gusts: 70 to 90 km/h with the highest gusts over exposed areas. Location: western Nova Scotia and Cumberland County. Time span: Light rain will begin today, intensify on Saturday, and move east of the province Saturday evening or overnight. Remarks: Rain is likely to switch to snow for some areas on Saturday evening as the system pulls away. Winds will strengthen ahead of this system, nearing warning levels for much of the province and there is a potential for power outages to occur. Conditions will improve Saturday night. In addition, higher than normal water levels are expected from Lunenburg east to Sheet Harbour near 4 am AST on Saturday. Wave heights of up to 6 metres are expected along the Atlantic coast beginning early Saturday and persisting most of the day. Coastal flooding is not expected at this time. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.
